abstract: Below are just few particularly well-dressed standouts from a monster crop of clothing stores that blanket the Manhattan map. If you're in the market for couture wear, the big-name designers have one or more boutiques in one or more locations: On Fifth Avenue in the 50's, on Madison Avenue and/or in SoHo.

abstract: A selective listing by critics of The Times of noteworthy pop and jazz concerts in the New York metropolitan region this weekend. * denotes a highly recommended concert.    ERIC ANDERSEN, Bottom Line, 15 West Fourth Street, at Mercer Street, Greenwich Village, (212) 228-6300. Since the 1960's, Eric Andersen has been picking his guitar and singing about love in wistfully graceful songs like ''Thirsty Boots'' and ''Blue River.'' Now, with a deeper, rougher voice, he has started to reflect about the passing decades; the title track of his new double album, ''Beat Avenue'' (Appleseed), is a 26-minute story over a jazz vamp about Beat poets on Nov. 22, 1963. Tonight at 7:30 and 10:30, with Lisa Cornelio opening; admission is $20 (Jon Pareles).

abstract: Ken Kalfus article on Philadelphia's diverse street scenes; photos (special section, The Sophisticated Traveler) (part 2 of 2-part section) (L)
snippet: Ken Kalfus article on Philadelphia's diverse street scenes; photos (special section, The Sophisticated Traveler) (part 2 of 2-part section) (L)
lead_paragraph: For a walk through one of America's last great walking cities, you should begin at the goat -- a small, eminently climbable bronze figure on the west side of Philadelphia's Rittenhouse Square. I've been coming to the goat for years, ever since my daughter, Sky, was a newborn, and it was at the goat, as a parent, that I was reintroduced to the city's distinct charms.
headline_main: PHILADELPHIA STREETS, REFINED AND LESS SO

abstract: A selective listing by critics of The Times of noteworthy pop and jazz concerts in the New York metropolitan region this weekend. * denotes a highly recommended concert.    * BEAT SCIENCE, JOE MORRIS TRIO, CBGB Lounge, 313 Bowery, East Village, (212) 677-0455. Beat Science is a septet from Boston, with Brian Carpenter on slide trumpet, Jim Hobbs on alto saxophone and Charlie Kohlhaase on baritone saxophone; it's a loose-limbed jazz group involving conducting of improvisers. Joe Morris's staccato, small-gesture guitar improvising was unique in the late 80's, when he started to get a little bit of attention, and remains that way today; his current band includes the remarkable bassist Timo Shanko and the drummer Luther Gray. Those sets are Sunday at 9 and 10; a four-band bill begins at 7. Admission is $10 (Ben Ratliff).

abstract: Adventures in Chocolate      The history and uses of chocolate are the subject of an exhibition through March 30 in the Everett Children's Adventure Garden at the New York Botanical Garden in the Bronx. Regular admission is $10 for adults, $7.50 for students and people over 65, and $4 for children 2 to 12: (718) 817-8700.
